You will need a promise for the `await`. The `get` of the `HttpClient` is returning Observable, while `await` is expecting a `promise`.

You can use `toPromise()` function to convert an Observable to a Promise.

You can also use the `Pipes` like `tap`, `catchError` and `finalize` to not subscribing the Observable inside the service. 

    return this.http.get (&#39;http://localhost:80/api/Target.xml&#39;,{ responseType: &#39;text&#39; })
      .pipe(
        tap(val =&gt; console.log(&quot;GET call successful value returned in body&quot;, val)),
        catchError(error =&gt; console.log(&quot;GET call in error&quot;, error)),
        finalize(() =&gt; console.log(&quot;The GET observable is now completed.&quot;))
      )
    ); 

For the commented part, even though you are using the `toPromise()`, it still won&#39;t work as if you put the logging right after the calling. 

async functions returns a promise which you should wait for then log the value. You either use the `then` like `ReadConfiguration().then(() =&gt; console.log(&quot;Completed&quot;))` or use another `async/await`.

